but Socrates and I always
knew that something happened.

988
01:08:36,279 --> 01:08:38,113
Oh, it's good to see you.

989
01:08:38,115 --> 01:08:40,715
You know, sometimes when
you stick up to "the man,"

990
01:08:40,717 --> 01:08:42,750
you get stuck with
a tranquilizer dart.

991
01:08:42,752 --> 01:08:45,186
- Were you able to stop Greene?
- Not yet.

992
01:08:45,188 --> 01:08:47,255
The houses are being
transported tonight.

993
01:08:47,257 --> 01:08:50,291
If we can stop them, maybe we
can stop this whole operation.

994
01:08:50,293 --> 01:08:52,694
Then what the heck
are you doing<i> here?</i>

995
01:08:55,565 --> 01:08:58,500
Norm, don't worry about me.
It's your time now.

996
01:08:58,502 --> 01:09:02,303
Leave me. Go! Save the arctic!
Save our homes.

997
01:09:02,305 --> 01:09:05,440
You<i> are</i> the arctic, grandpa.

998
01:09:07,777 --> 01:09:11,279
Hmm. I must have
weakened them for you.

999
01:09:11,281 --> 01:09:13,214
What do you say
we go save our home?

1000
01:09:33,470 --> 01:09:34,802
What?

1001
01:09:37,707 --> 01:09:39,474
The arctic rats?

1002
01:09:44,181 --> 01:09:47,815
What?

1003
01:09:47,817 --> 01:09:49,717
What do you mean the bear
broke out of the cage?

1004
01:09:49,719 --> 01:09:51,920
It's impossible.
He's like, 80.

1005
01:09:51,922 --> 01:09:53,855
It would have taken
two bears to...

1006
01:09:55,926 --> 01:09:58,860
<i>What?
That isn't norm!</i>

1007
01:09:58,862 --> 01:10:01,696
Get the chopper
and find two polar bears!

1008
01:10:04,734 --> 01:10:06,801
How long until the ship leaves?

1009
01:10:06,803 --> 01:10:09,237
I don't care if they're
predicting a storm.

1010
01:10:09,239 --> 01:10:11,606
- Leave now!

1011
01:10:11,608 --> 01:10:14,509
The houses are on
the way to the arctic!

1012
01:10:14,511 --> 01:10:16,844
We gotta get to them!

1013
01:10:34,664 --> 01:10:36,497
Where are we headed?

1014
01:10:36,499 --> 01:10:37,765
Same place where I came in.

1015
01:10:48,011 --> 01:10:51,946
Huh?

1016
01:10:51,948 --> 01:10:53,948
<i>There they are!</i>

1017
01:10:53,950 --> 01:10:57,552
Get ready, grandpa.
There's our ride home.

1018
01:11:09,532 --> 01:11:12,300
Agh-hh!

1019
01:11:12,302 --> 01:11:15,603
- Ow!

1020
01:11:15,605 --> 01:11:17,472
No!

1021
01:11:19,809 --> 01:11:21,743
Eh...?

1022
01:11:38,762 --> 01:11:40,395
<i>If we don't get down there,
it's gonna be</i>

1023
01:11:40,397 --> 01:11:42,730
a long swim to the arctic.

1024
01:11:52,842 --> 01:11:55,743
Oh-hh. Hey!

1025
01:12:06,456 --> 01:12:07,855
Just shoot those bears.

1026
01:12:07,857 --> 01:12:09,657
Greene said to put them
out of their misery

1027
01:12:09,659 --> 01:12:12,593
- and dump 'em in the ocean.
- Wait! Wait!

1028
01:12:12,595 --> 01:12:14,462
You guys think we're bears?

1029
01:12:14,464 --> 01:12:16,030
You hear that, grandpa?

1030
01:12:16,032 --> 01:12:20,868
Talking polar bears in Manhattan?
Now, come on, guys.

1031
01:12:20,870 --> 01:12:23,504
Yeah, maybe our friend the
Easter bunny's around here, too.

1032
01:12:24,641 --> 01:12:26,641
Are you sure they're bears?

1033
01:12:26,643 --> 01:12:28,710
<i>They sound like humans to me.</i>

1034
01:12:28,712 --> 01:12:30,812
<i>- I didn't sign up
to shoot real people.</i>

1035
01:13:35,645 --> 01:13:37,011
Hmm.

1036
01:14:05,442 --> 01:14:07,575
Norm, no matter what happens,

1037
01:14:07,577 --> 01:14:09,744
just know that I'm proud of you.

1038
01:14:09,746 --> 01:14:11,913
You've come a long way.

1039
01:14:11,915 --> 01:14:15,650
You might think you're not
a hunter, but you are.

1040
01:14:15,652 --> 01:14:18,586
<i>Your way of hunting is just
different than everyone else.</i>

1041
01:14:18,588 --> 01:14:22,089
You're going to make
a great king one day.

1042
01:14:22,091 --> 01:14:24,659
I know it.

1043
01:14:24,661 --> 01:14:26,160
What's wrong?

1044
01:14:26,162 --> 01:14:27,795
We're gonna get this, norm.

1045
01:14:27,797 --> 01:14:29,697
No, sorry.
It's not about that.

1046
01:14:29,699 --> 01:14:32,667
I... I'm just worried.
In saving our own home,

1047
01:14:32,669 --> 01:14:35,203
I may have ruined
someone else's.

1048
01:14:35,205 --> 01:14:38,773
I'm just hoping Vera and
Olympia will be okay.

1049
01:15:04,000 --> 01:15:05,800
<i>It's beautiful, mom,</i>

1050
01:15:05,802 --> 01:15:07,902
<i>but what will it look like
when you and Mr. Greene</i>

1051
01:15:07,904 --> 01:15:09,871
<i>build all those houses there?</i>

1052
01:15:15,245 --> 01:15:17,545
"Mr. Greene, I'm sorry,

1053
01:15:17,547 --> 01:15:19,580
but I cannot help you
destroy somebody's home

1054
01:15:19,582 --> 01:15:21,983
in order to build
houses no one needs.

1055
01:15:21,985 --> 01:15:23,851
I quit."

1056
01:15:33,229 --> 01:15:35,663
Okay, every office
around the world

1057
01:15:35,665 --> 01:15:37,832
is ready to feed this.
Are you sure, Pablo?

1058
01:15:37,834 --> 01:15:40,968
Yes.
Send it now.

1059
01:15:48,811 --> 01:15:51,178
We have to dislodge this barge

1060
01:15:51,180 --> 01:15:53,147
so we can flip these houses.

1061
01:15:53,149 --> 01:15:56,050
These condos must never
reach the arctic.

1062
01:16:00,590 --> 01:16:03,024
Buckle up, guys.
This could get bumpy.

1063
01:16:08,598 --> 01:16:11,132
We have to do this, now.

1064
01:16:18,241 --> 01:16:20,708
It won't dislodge,
it's too rough.

1065
01:16:20,710 --> 01:16:23,044
The swells keep pushing it back.

1066
01:16:55,278 --> 01:16:58,879
Welcome to the real north shore!

1067
01:17:02,318 --> 01:17:05,686
See you on the other side...
whichever one we get to.

1068
01:17:05,688 --> 01:17:08,189
But remember, whatever happens,

1069
01:17:08,191 --> 01:17:12,159
a king always fights
for his home!

1070
01:17:13,730 --> 01:17:16,664
Come on, lemmings!

1071
01:18:01,444 --> 01:18:05,046
<i>A king always fights
for his home.</i>

1072
01:18:18,695 --> 01:18:20,461
Le...

1073
01:18:20,463 --> 01:18:24,198
Lemmings! Grandpa!

1074
01:18:36,112 --> 01:18:37,445
Talk to me.

1075
01:18:37,447 --> 01:18:40,114
What the...
They never got there?

1076
01:18:40,116 --> 01:18:42,216
Then where are my condos?

1077
01:18:42,218 --> 01:18:44,485
The bottom of the ocean?

1078
01:18:44,487 --> 01:18:46,454
Is that some kinda joke?

1079
01:18:46,456 --> 01:18:49,490
Two polar bears?

1080
01:18:54,263 --> 01:18:57,064
<i>"Greene homes and polar
council under investigation</i>

1081
01:18:57,066 --> 01:19:00,067
for bribery charges?

1082
01:19:00,069 --> 01:19:02,803
<i>Beloved norm helps reveal sham"?</i>

1083
01:19:02,805 --> 01:19:07,875
These condos weren't for any
of you peasants anyway.

1084
01:19:07,877 --> 01:19:10,811
They were for the one percent.
The one percent!

1085
01:19:16,786 --> 01:19:21,188
Huh, would you look at that?
I'm late for yoga.

1086
01:19:21,190 --> 01:19:22,890
Namaste, everybody.

1087
01:19:22,892 --> 01:19:24,525
- Janet?
- Whatever.

1088
01:19:24,527 --> 01:19:27,128
- <i>Janet!</i>

1089
01:19:27,130 --> 01:19:29,263
<i>Help me, you peasants!
Help me!</i>

1090
01:19:29,265 --> 01:19:31,899
<i>Don't you know
who I am? Huh?</i>

1091
01:19:31,901 --> 01:19:35,936
<i>Rats! They're crawling on me!
This is Italian!</i>

1092
01:19:44,113 --> 01:19:47,815
Look who's out of hibernation.

1093
01:19:47,817 --> 01:19:49,817
Son.

1094
01:19:51,888 --> 01:19:55,189
Every time I see you,
you've fallen on your butt.

1095
01:19:55,191 --> 01:19:57,324
I march to the beat of my own drum.
You know that.

1096
01:19:57,326 --> 01:19:59,527
When everyone else
stands, I sit.

1097
01:19:59,529 --> 01:20:00,895
<i>Ta-da!</i>

1098
01:20:00,897 --> 01:20:02,830
Lemmings!
You made it!

1099
01:20:02,832 --> 01:20:06,233
Where's grandpa?
Did he...?

1100
01:20:06,235 --> 01:20:09,303
We've searched everywhere, norm.

1101
01:20:10,873 --> 01:20:13,407
No.

1102
01:20:25,254 --> 01:20:27,254
Norm, you saved our home.

1103
01:20:27,256 --> 01:20:29,223
I'm sorry I didn't
realize until now,

1104
01:20:29,225 --> 01:20:32,026
but we are so proud of you.

1105
01:20:32,028 --> 01:20:34,128
The lemmings told us
what you've done.

1106
01:20:34,130 --> 01:20:37,031
You used your gift
and you risked your life

1107
01:20:37,033 --> 01:20:39,099
to protect ours.

1108
01:20:39,101 --> 01:20:42,903
And on behalf of all of us...

1109
01:20:42,905 --> 01:20:44,405
Thank you.

1110
01:20:48,110 --> 01:20:52,479
Ahem. Remember
what we discussed?

1111
01:20:54,350 --> 01:20:56,450
<i>A new day dawns upon us.</i>

1112
01:20:56,452 --> 01:20:58,986
We need a leader who feels
for the arctic,

1113
01:20:58,988 --> 01:21:03,591
speaks for the arctic,
and always fights for our home.

1114
01:21:03,593 --> 01:21:06,060
<i>Norm, I crown you...</i>

1115
01:21:06,062 --> 01:21:09,196
Now just a New York minute.

1116
01:21:09,198 --> 01:21:11,599
You can't do this without me.

1117
01:21:11,601 --> 01:21:13,968
Grandpa!

1118
01:21:19,508 --> 01:21:21,876
They all said you drowned.

1119
01:21:21,878 --> 01:21:24,078
I was 80% sure
you were gonna make it.

1120
01:21:26,315 --> 01:21:29,617
Now<i> that's</i> what I call
a grand entrance.

1121
01:21:29,619 --> 01:21:31,952
The tide took me all
the way to Greenland,

1122
01:21:31,954 --> 01:21:33,587
but I hitched a ride
with an Orca.

1123
01:21:33,589 --> 01:21:37,958
He said he was coming back
to audition for Stan.

1124
01:21:37,960 --> 01:21:41,195
You need therapy.

1125
01:21:41,197 --> 01:21:44,298
I have an opening tomorrow afternoon.
Book yourself in.

1126
01:21:44,300 --> 01:21:46,567
Son, please continue.

1127
01:21:46,569 --> 01:21:49,570
Norm, I crown you king.

1128
01:21:59,482 --> 01:22:02,917
- That's my brother! Yeah!

1129
01:22:19,635 --> 01:22:22,403
If the clouds clear
and the barometric pressure

1130
01:22:22,405 --> 01:22:24,638
is just right...

1131
01:22:24,640 --> 01:22:27,274
Wow. I see Magister
Mundi is teaching you

1132
01:22:27,276 --> 01:22:30,277
all these fancy
new terms already.

1133
01:22:30,279 --> 01:22:33,714
I told you I could do it
on my own, without Greene.

1134
01:22:33,716 --> 01:22:36,450
Aren't you liking it without Mr.
Greene in your life, too?

1135
01:22:36,452 --> 01:22:39,453
Pablo seems like
a much better boss.

1136
01:22:39,455 --> 01:22:42,456
Well, norm gave me
a great recommendation.

1137
01:22:42,458 --> 01:22:44,558
Oh, my gosh!
I can see it.

1138
01:22:44,560 --> 01:22:46,527
I can finally see it.

1139
01:22:49,565 --> 01:22:53,968
He even looks like norm.
I miss him, mom.

1140
01:22:53,970 --> 01:22:56,570
Me, too. But I know
he made it home.

1141
01:22:56,572 --> 01:22:59,139
I bet he has his own family now.

1142
01:23:21,130 --> 01:23:24,598
Isn't it pretty?

1143
01:23:24,600 --> 01:23:30,137
Yeah. I wonder if Vera and
Olympia can see this, too.

1144
01:23:30,139 --> 01:23:32,172
<i>- Whoa!
- They're beautiful!</i>

1145
01:24:58,360 --> 01:25:00,394
<i>Wait for it. Wait for it...</i>

1146
01:25:04,166 --> 01:25:06,300
Yah!
Ta-da!

